The petition to King and Council of Scolastica, widow of Godfrey de Meaux. She holds Levisham manor by lease from Master Thomas de Levisham, to whom the King leased it during the minority of John, the son and heir of Godfrey 3 to which manor the bailiwick of Scalby Hay is appurtenant, being held at a rent of A 3 38· 4d-† After the death of Godfrey, Thomas Earl of Lancaster seized the bailiwick into his hands because the heir was under age, and he wished to receive the rent from the bailiwick. Now the bailiwick has come into the King’s hands through the Earl's forfeiture‚ and Scolastica prays the King that she may have the bailiwick which is appurtenant to the manor, paying the rent up (0 (116 time of the heir’s majority, of which the King has no profit.
